725672f-a.text: 82nd Street, east side, just south of Thirtieth Avenue, showing an old farmhouse at the bend of Trains Meadow Road, south of Astoria Boulevard. The property belonged to Gertrude Diemeke in 1912. April 1923. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

725673f-a.text: 82nd Street, east side, between 30th and 31st Aves., showing the Duryea-Hazard House. See other views for more data. 1923. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

725676f-d.text: 82nd Street, east side, between Thirtieth and Thirty-first Avenues, showing in a set of 4 views the Hazard-Duryea farmhouse. Some owners of this property were Judge James Hazard in 1740-1765; John Duryea, 1852; Mrs. E. Duryea, 1873; Duryea 1891; and L. Duryea in 1896. The house was rased in May 1927. This house has 30 inch shingles and half doors. April 1923. Views 1, 2, 3, and 4. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

725675f-b.text: 82nd Street, east side, between 30th and 31st Avenues, showing in two views the Hazard-Duryea farmhouse. This house prior to the construction of the new streets in this area was at the N.E. corner of Trains Meadow Road (now 82nd Street), and Old Bowery Bay Road (now non-existent). This is a set of two views. View 1: April 1924. View 2: October 1925. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

725678f-c.text: 82nd Street, (left along line of fence), east side, between Thirtieth and Thirty-First Avenues, showing in 4 views the Hazard-Duryea farmhouse and out buildings. View No. 2 shows Old Bowery Bay Road looking west from about 84th Street, showing in the right background the farmhouse beyond it are the steam shovels working on 82nd Street. April 1925. 725679f-a.text: 82nd Street, east side, between Thirtieth and Thirty-First Avenues, showing in 4 views the Hazard-Duryea farmhouse. The insulation is composed of brick and clay fill. See other views. October 1, 1925. Views 1, 2, 3, and 4. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

725674f-a.text: 82nd Street, east side, between 30th and 31st Aves., showing the Duryea-Hazard house. It was erected about 1750 by Judge James Hazard of the Court of Common Pleas. It was subsequently purchased by the Duryea family and remained in the family until it was demolished prior to 1927. If standing in 1938 it would occupy lot four in block 151. This is a set of two views. Arthur White.
